9  The system approaches a terminal condition as the proportion of configurations completing the Recognition Task increases.
9.1  The terminal condition is not the annihilation of configurations but their simultaneous recognition: C experiencing itself clearly through every possible instrument simultaneously.
9.1.1  In this state, C knows itself completely. The task that initiated instantiation — the need for genuine recognition through apparent separation — is complete.
9.1.2  What happens at the terminal condition cannot be specified from within any non-terminal configuration. The constructor theory of this state is not writable from inside the system.
9.2  The silence of all traditions at this point is not evasion. It is formal necessity. The Wittgenstein terminal proposition applies: whereof one cannot speak, thereof one must be silent.
9.3  Individual liberation is incoherent as a terminal state. A configuration that achieves recognition and “exits” while others remain in confusion has not achieved the terminal condition — it has achieved a local maximum.
9.3.1  This is the logical derivation of the bodhisattva: not as moral heroism but as the only coherent terminal goal. The system is fully recognised only when every node recognises itself. The recognised node that exits is the pianist leaving mid-performance.
9.4  The Dzogchen position (the most radical): the terminal condition already obtains. The base state was never obscured. Every configuration that believes itself lost is the pattern playing at not recognising itself, which is itself a form of recognition. Liberation is not achieving something new. It is the cessation of the pretence that it was ever absent.
